\begin_layout Standard
\align block
The predominant view of status in empirical economics has relied on a hierarchy
 of social ranks or occupations.
 While empirical studies tend to explore status concerns separately from
 economic concerns, the literature in sociology has also been concerned
 with how status perceptions relate with economic goals.
 The sociological literature has thus focussed on the issue of closure in
 social groups and attempted to reconcile the subjective and objective aspects
 of status.
 The current chapter leans towards approaches in economics that consider
 a dynamism in the hierarchical order for status.
 To provide a structural basis for the link between economic and social
 goals, the current chapter uses probability functions that determine the
 promotion and demotion of participants among rich and poor classes in an
 economy.
 The chances to win and to be promoted to the rich class in a competition
 depends on social capital - which are skills that can be enhanced with
 expenditure - as well as raw-talent which are not affected by higher expenditur
e.
 Assuming a diminishing returns to utility from wealth, the chapter then
 argues that an equilibrium with expenditure towards promotion leads to
 two primary states in the economy - one where both rich and poor strive
 for status and the other where only rich the consumers participate in status
 competitions.
 The chapter also argues that a rise in income differences incentivises
 the poor to participate in the status competition.
\end_layout

