\begin_layout Standard
While the predominant view of status in empirical economics remains one
 that is based on hierarchy of ranks (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goldthorpeOccupationalGrading1975,wegener1992prestigeconcepts,goldthorpesociology2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), several attempts have been made in both sociology and economics to view
 status in a more dynamic framework (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925,shilsDeference1969,parsonssystemsocieties1971,ColemanSocialTheory1990,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Instead of treating status goals separate from economic goals, the presented
 chapter pins down a specific link between economics and social goals relevant
 for status consumption by allowing an indirect (instrumental) effect of
 status on consumer wealth (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A contrast between economic and social goals seems to have generated more
 interest in the sociological literature where the issue of reconciliation
 of the subjective aspects of status (the effect of status differences on
 individual behaviour) and its objective aspects (the observed reality of
 status differences) has gathered some attention (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The sociological literature uses both hierarchical order (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ) and conflict in social aggregates (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) to address this particular issue.
 Several approaches in economics have also incorporated the views from the
 literature that prescribe a dynamism in social order (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes,moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The current chapter relies upon views from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who view that status as a product of economic processes that is shaped
 by institutional nurturing or discouragement of individual attributes (also
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Given the wide-differences in the level of economic development that is
 often observed across developing economies (such as Tanzania and Nigeria),
 we find the endogenisation of status suitable for a generic framework that
 can be used to compare disparate developing economies.
 
\end_layout

