\begin_layout Standard
It is often argued that status is a social rather than economic goal for
 an individual.
 Yet the difference between social and economic goals of the individual
 remains hardly well-defined in both sociology or economics.
 The idea that status is orthogonal to economic goals - the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure status
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 view (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ) - seldom fits with the real-world observations where status both contributes
 to income and improves with rises in income.
 Indeed the other extreme view that the economic goals alone motivate status
 competitions - so that status is derived purely from economic rewards is
 also unrealistic.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue, the reality is often somewhere in between the two extremes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A structural model for this interplay between economic and social goals
 is however yet to specified in either sociology or economics.
 The dominant view for status in both sociology and economics has been one
 that is based on hierarchy and social deference (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990,goldthorpesociology2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - a view that is inherent in occupational status surveys widely used in
 empirical studies (e.g.
 the EGP classes or the Goldthorpe class scheme).
 A fundamental problem that the sociology literature has elaborated (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) in empirical analyses is a failure to reconcile the difference between
 objective aspects of status (the observed reality of status differences)
 and its subjective aspects (the effect of status differences on individual
 behaviour).
 An evident issue with addressing only the objective aspect of status using
 a utilitarian model while leaving the subjective aspect exogenous is that
 status may never be explained in economic terms while an economy for status
 is ruled out.
 As many have argued, the idea of social-closure (aggregate or stÃ¤nde first
 discussed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) in sociology cannot be conflated with that of social ranks (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Indeed the issue is not merely a theoretical one.
 It has been suggested that the subjective evaluations of status often measure
 an overall desirability of occupations rather than status (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goldthorpeOccupationalGrading1975"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "adlerstatuscomponents1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue that skills or knowledge of individuals may better predict the individual
 judgments of status.
 Further, the scales of status used in empirical studies are also observed
 to vary significantly across the sections of a society (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ackerwomenstratification1980"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several approaches have aimed to reconcile the difference between objective
 and subjective aspects of status (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 addresses the issue by simply ensuring that the subjective and objective
 aspects coincide in status-related interpretations.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues that the basic categories in terms of which we describe a system
 of hierarchies as a structure is the same as those in terms of which individual
 behavior or performance should be defined.
 While culture places a premium on equality, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues, the distribution rules in different social subsystems are not aimed
 at generating equality - thus letting status exist to assert basic importance
