\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\equiv\frac{\mu}{8(1-\mu)}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}\equiv1-2p_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}'\equiv\frac{19\mu^{2}-40\mu+20}{40(1-\mu)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}'\equiv1-2p_{1}'$
\end_inset

 which correspond to the three-player model discussed above.
 The consumer choices for the poor and rich participants using a general
 intertemporally additive function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A)$
\end_inset

 (for assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

) are shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:prisoners_dilemma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 As we can verify from Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Probability-of-winning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}<1/3<p_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}'>1/3>p_{2}'$
\end_inset

 for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu<1/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\text{Given }\mu<1/2,\text{we have}\label{eq:probability_inequality}\\
p_{1}<1/3<p_{2}\nonumber \\
p_{1}'>1/3>p_{2}'\nonumber 
\end{gather}

